{
  "texts": [
    "(3)Similarly, Focal Loss (FL), Mean Absolute Error (MAE), and Reverse Cross Entropy (RCE) can be normalized to obtain Normalized Focal Loss (NFL), Normalized Mean Absolute Error (NMAE), and Normalized Reverse Cross Entropy (NRCE), respectively.",
    "However, a normalized loss function alone suffers from underfitting.",
    "To address this issue, Ma et al. [14] categorized loss functions into two types: Active and Passive.They first rewrite the loss function L(f (x), y) in an expectation form, such that L(f (x), y) = K k=1 ℓ(f (x), k) (e.g., let L be CE, then L(f (x), y) = K k=1 q(k|x)(log p(k|x)), and ℓ(f (x), k) = q(k|x)(log p(k|x))).",
    "Based on this, the two types of loss functions are defined as follows:Definition 1 (Active loss function).",
    "L Active is an active loss function if ∀(x, y) ∈ D, ∀k ̸ = y, ℓ(f (x), k) = 0."
  ]
}